Certainly! Here's a comprehensive example showing how to automatically generate a **detailed** Table of Contents (ToC), including numbering, subsections, figures with titles in ToC, captions for tables, cross-references, and more - all within a LaTeX document using the standard `book` class along with the `tocbibind`, `hyperref`, and `tocstyle` packages:

```latex
\documentclass[11pt,oneside]{book}

\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{tocbibind} % Include bibliography and figures in ToC
\usepackage{hyperref} % For clickable links and automatic ToC generation
\usepackage{tocstyle}  % For customizing the ToC format and appearance

\hypersetup{
  colorlinks=true,
  linkcolor=blue,
  bookmarks=true
}

\tocstyle{
  numbered
  % Other customizations can go here, e.g., \tocHline, \tocentries repeatedly for styling
}

\title{Example Book}
\author{Author Name}
\date{}
\begin{document}

\frontmatter % For roman page numbering

\tableofcontents

\mainmatter
\part{Part One: Introduction}
\chapter{Chapter 1: Introduction}
\section{Section 1.1: Details}
\section{Section 1.2: More Details with a Figure}
  \begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{example-figure}
    \caption{Example Figure Title}
  \end{figure}

% For table with caption to appear in the ToC: Declare it as a figure or use 'caption' package
\begin{table}[htbp]
    \centering
    \caption{Example Table Title}
    \begin{tabular}{...} % your table content
    \end{tabular}
    \label{tab:mytable}
\end{table}
\ldots (repeating for many chapters, sections, subsections)

\backmatter % For arabic page numbering
\bibliography{your-bib-file}

\end{document}
```

The key commands for **automatic** Table of Contents generation are loaded with the `hyperref` package (which hooks into all cross-referencing commands and updates the ToC accordingly) alongside with `\tableofcontents` that directly creates the ToC. The `tocbibind` package ensures all bibliography items and floats (figures, tables, etc.) are included in the ToC.

After running this LaTeX document with a build system or using `pdflatex`, a properly generated, clickable ToC with all desired elements will be created at the document's beginning. The `tocstyle` package provides additional flexibility in formatting, and when combined with automatic hyperlinking, it results in a professionally styled, interactive ToC. The ToC will automatically update after any changes to the document structure due to insertions or deletions of sections, subsections, figures, tables, etc.

